                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (Requisitions)/15: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-06T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 6, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>183. Your 418, June 6, 11 a.m.<note n="94" xml:id="d623fn94">Not printed.</note>
                    The Department has no objection to your communicating orally to Japanese
                    officials and to the press, as an <pb facs="0584" n="576" xml:id="pg_576"/>
                    informal expression of your understanding of this phase of the Government’s
                    national defense program, the substance of the Department’s 179, June 4, 1 [<hi
                        rend="italic">10</hi>] p.m., but it is not desired that the language of that
                    telegram be given textually to the press or published in the press as a
                    quotation.</p>
                <p>Some of the statements contained in the telegram in question have been orally
                    communicated in informal language to press correspondents here, but no statement
                    in the matter is being issued by the Department at the present time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
